<p><b>George P. Lakoff</b> (pronounced <span title="Pronunciation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:IPA_for_English" title="Wikipedia:IPA for English">/ˈleɪkɒf/</a></span>, born <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1941-05-24"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="05-24"><a href="/wiki/May_24" title="May 24">May 24</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/1941" title="1941">1941</a></span>) is a professor of <a href="/wiki/Cognitive_linguistics" title="Cognitive linguistics">cognitive linguistics</a> at the <a href="/wiki/University_of_California,_Berkeley" title="University of California, Berkeley">University of California, Berkeley</a>, where he has taught at since 1972. Although some of his research involves questions traditionally pursued by linguists, such as the conditions under which a certain linguistic construction is grammatically viable, he is most famous for his ideas about the centrality of <a href="/wiki/Conceptual_metaphor" title="Conceptual metaphor">metaphor</a> to human thinking, political behavior and society. He is particularly famous for his concept of the "<a href="/wiki/Embodied_philosophy" title="Embodied philosophy" class="mw-redirect">embodied mind</a>," which he has written about in relation to <a href="/wiki/Mathematics" title="Mathematics">mathematics</a>. In recent years he has applied his work to the realm of <a href="/wiki/Politics" title="Politics">politics</a>, exploring this in <a href="/wiki/George_Lakoff#Selected_bibliography" title="George Lakoff">his books</a>. He was the founder of the now defunct <a href="/wiki/Progressivism" title="Progressivism">progressive</a> <a href="/wiki/Think_tank" title="Think tank">think tank</a> the <a href="/wiki/Rockridge_Institute" title="Rockridge Institute">Rockridge Institute</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Moral_Politics_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Moral_Politics-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
